======================================================================
SUMMARY: Maximum alpha_1 with alpha_2=0 (all-conflicting)
======================================================================

STRUCTURAL ANALYSIS:
If all odd cycles pairwise share a vertex, consider the
'conflict hypergraph' where each cycle is a hyperedge.
A clique in the conflict graph = a set of cycles, every pair sharing a vertex.
This is like a 'sunflower' (or near-sunflower) structure.

Key theorem (Helly for cycles): If d+1 convex sets in R^d
are pairwise intersecting, they have a common point.
For vertex sets of size 3 (3-cycles): Helly dimension 2
=> 3 pairwise-intersecting 3-cycles SHOULD have a common vertex
... unless they violate convexity (which discrete sets always can).

But the splicing lemma (opus-S71e) shows that even without
a common vertex, extra cycles are forced, so a1=3 with a2=0
is impossible regardless.
